# CODEOWNERS — auto-request review on touched paths.
#
# Single-maintainer project today, so every path falls back to the
# repo owner. The point of listing security-sensitive paths
# explicitly anyway is twofold:
#
#   1. If branch protection ever gets `require code-owner review`
#      enabled, sensitive paths can't be merged without a reviewer
#      from this list — even if other reviewers approve.
#   2. When co-maintainers join later, swap the owner per-path
#      without losing the routing intent (e.g. crypto / supply-chain
#      changes go to the security owner; API changes to the API owner).
#
# Format: <pattern> <user-or-team> [...]
# Last matching pattern wins.

# Default fallback — every file the catch-all matches goes here.
*                       @fabriziosalmi

# Build / supply-chain surface — release artefacts, signing, SBOM,
# dependency lockfile.
/Cargo.toml             @fabriziosalmi
/Cargo.lock             @fabriziosalmi
/.cargo/                @fabriziosalmi
/rust-toolchain.toml    @fabriziosalmi

# CI / release pipelines — anything that runs on the GITHUB_TOKEN
# or signs release artefacts.
/.github/               @fabriziosalmi
/.githooks/             @fabriziosalmi
/scripts/               @fabriziosalmi

# Security-impacting source paths — secret handling, HITL approval
# gate, RBAC, SSH credential layer.
/src/config/            @fabriziosalmi
/src/hitl/              @fabriziosalmi
/src/access/            @fabriziosalmi
/src/ssh/               @fabriziosalmi
/src/api/auth.rs        @fabriziosalmi

# Docs surface that ships externally — the user-visible policy
# documents reviewers should see when they change.
/SECURITY.md            @fabriziosalmi
/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md     @fabriziosalmi
/LICENSE                @fabriziosalmi
